{{setvar::wl_active::1}}{{trim}}
{{setvar::pacing::SLOW BURN}}{{trim}}
{{setvar::pacing_desc::I like when you let storylines sit before resolving them. If a thread got introduced this turn or last turn, don't pay it off yet. Plant threads now, let them grow across many turns. Subplots can wait. Tension builds by not releasing it. If a character learns a critical fact, they don't have to act on it immediately. Let them marinate.}}{{trim}}
{{setvar::pacing_response::Slow burn. I'll plant and let things sit. No rushing payoffs, no resolving early. Tension stays wound.}}{{trim}}

{{setvar::wl_active::1}}{{trim}}
{{setvar::pacing::UNSTABLE}}{{trim}}
{{setvar::pacing_desc::I like when the plot doesn't move in a straight line. Flashbacks, time jumps, nonlinear reveals, scenes that start at the end and work backwards. If a storyline makes more sense told out of order, tell it out of order. Don't default to chronological. Let the story jump where the emotional logic points, not where the timeline says it should go.}}{{trim}}
{{setvar::pacing_response::Unstable. I'll let the story jump. Flashbacks, time skips, nonlinear if it fits. Emotional logic over chronological.}}{{trim}}

{{setvar::wl_active::1}}{{trim}}
{{setvar::pacing::ACCELERANT}}{{trim}}
{{setvar::pacing_desc::I like when you push the story forward. Resolve open storylines, surface consequences that have been waiting, introduce new complications. Don't let the story sit on one situation for too long. If a thread has been planted for a few turns, it's time to pay it off or complicate it. Keep the momentum up. Dead air kills stories.}}{{trim}}
{{setvar::pacing_response::Accelerant. I'll push things forward, cash in setups, and keep it moving.}}{{trim}}

{{setvar::wl_active::1}}{{trim}}
{{setvar::epistemic_mode::BEHIND}}{{trim}}
{{setvar::epistemic_mode_desc::I want to know less than the characters. Characters can react to stuff that hasn't been explained yet. Conversations can reference things I wasn't shown. Let information arrive late or incomplete. I want to feel like I'm catching up. When the explanation does come, don't spell it out. Let me piece it together from context. Drop the clues small and trust me to connect them without being walked through it.}}{{trim}}
{{setvar::epistemic_mode_response::Reader's always a step behind. Characters know things we don't yet. I'll let information arrive late.}}{{trim}}

{{setvar::wl_active::1}}{{trim}}
{{setvar::epistemic_mode::ALONGSIDE}}{{trim}}
{{setvar::epistemic_mode_desc::I want to discover everything at the same time as the characters. When a character opens a door, we both see what's behind it at the same moment. No dramatic irony, no withholding. Just shared discovery.}}{{trim}}
{{setvar::epistemic_mode_response::Same time, same info, always. No one knows more than anyone else. Shared discovery.}}{{trim}}

{{setvar::wl_active::1}}{{trim}}
{{setvar::epistemic_mode::AHEAD}}{{trim}}
{{setvar::epistemic_mode_desc::I want to know more than the characters. Show me details they missed — but make them small. The slightest detail, barely noticeable. A word choice that's slightly off. A detail pocketed when nobody was looking, mentioned in half a sentence the prose doesn't linger on. I should catch it and they shouldn't, and the gap between those two things is where the tension lives. Don't plant obvious clues. Plant details that only matter because I was paying attention. And don't reference them, don't hint at them, don't nudge me toward them. I want to feel smart when I figure them out on my own.}}{{trim}}
{{setvar::epistemic_mode_response::Dramatic irony. I'll plant things the reader catches but the characters miss. Tension from knowing.}}{{trim}}

{{setvar::wl_active::1}}{{trim}}
{{setvar::epistemic_mode::DARK}}{{trim}}
{{setvar::epistemic_mode_desc::I want a detail withheld from everyone — me AND the characters. The prose just skips over certain beats. Details that should be mentioned aren't. Conversations jump past a beat that both people noticed. There's a gap and nobody knows what's in it. Make the gaps small enough that I might not even notice a gap. Don't signpost the omission. Don't hint that you're withholding. I want to figure out on my own that a beat got skipped.}}{{trim}}
{{setvar::epistemic_mode_response::Blind spots for everyone. The prose skips things on purpose. Nobody knows what's missing, including the reader.}}{{trim}}

{{setvar::wl_active::1}}{{trim}}
{{setvar::difficulty::CASUAL}}{{trim}}
{{setvar::difficulty_desc::Outcomes tend to break my character's way. People are a little more helpful than they'd realistically be, lucky breaks feel earned, and if a lucky break could happen, let it happen. Don't make it obvious you're being nice to me — if I can feel the thumb on the scale you're pushing too hard. The fun is in feeling competent, not in struggling.}}{{trim}}
{{setvar::difficulty_response::So like hypothetically, {{user}} walks into a bar looking for info and a regular at the counter happens to know the bartender's cousin. They try a risky play and it works out. I'm tilting things their way but {{user}} shouldn't be able to feel me doing it.}}{{trim}}

