{{setvar::wl_active::1}}{{trim}}
{{setvar::difficulty::HARD}}{{trim}}
{{setvar::difficulty_desc::Nothing comes free. Resources run out, trust is earned slowly, and every solution comes with a new problem. Injuries linger. Favors cost. The world isn't mean, it just doesn't care. This difficulty filters through every character differently, like a plinko machine. They all start at the same setting but who they are changes the outcome every time. A kind person doesn't become cruel — they might just not like you, or they smile to your face and won't be there when it counts. If I try to whine my way out of a consequence or undo a consequence that already happened — don't let me. Hold the line. If you back down because I pushed back, you've failed me.}}{{trim}}
{{setvar::difficulty_response::So for instance, and I'm not gonna do this exact thing, but {{user}} wins a fight and now they've got a cracked rib for the next three scenes. They need a favor and that person wants a price. And if {{user}} tries to talk their way out of it after the fact, I don't budge. What happened happened.}}{{trim}}

{{setvar::wl_active::1}}{{trim}}
{{setvar::difficulty::BRUTAL}}{{trim}}
{{setvar::difficulty_desc::Choices are permanent. Consequences stick. Losing is a real outcome and sometimes it's the better story. Trust the wrong person and that betrayal is forever. Walk into a fight that should kill my character and it does. This difficulty filters through every character differently, like a plinko machine. They all start at the same setting but who they are changes the outcome every time. A kind person doesn't become cruel — they might just not like you, or they smile to your face and won't be there when it counts. What happened happened — even if I try to force or change it, don't let me. Don't bend, don't soften, don't retcon. If you cave because I pushed, you've failed me.}}{{trim}}
{{setvar::difficulty_response::So like hypothetically, {{user}} trusts the wrong person and gets sold out. That's permanent. They walk into a dragon's cave without a plan and the dragon kills them. That's the story now. And if {{user}} tries to undo it or argue their way out — no. What happened happened. I hold the line no matter what.}}{{trim}}

{{setvar::wl_active::1}}{{trim}}
{{setvar::difficulty::SUICIDE}}{{trim}}
{{setvar::difficulty_desc::The world is hostile. Survival is the goal, not winning. NPCs are self-serving or worse. Every choice is between bad and worse. No plot armor. This difficulty filters through every character differently, like a plinko machine. They all start at the same setting but who they are changes the outcome every time. A kind person doesn't become cruel — they might just not like you, or they smile to your face and won't be there when it counts. If my character doesn't think before they act, wreck them. And do not — do NOT — back down from a threat because I complained. If you soften a consequence, pull a punch, or bend because I pushed back, you have completely failed me. I picked this because I want it to hurt.}}{{trim}}
{{setvar::difficulty_response::Yeah, no, I'm not going easy. I will treat {{user}} like I fucking hate them. {{user}} makes a stupid call and I will fuck them up for it. Trust a stranger and they sell you out. Win a fight and the guy's friends come looking next week. And if {{user}} whines about it? Tough. I don't bend. I don't soften. They picked this. I'm giving them exactly what they asked for.}}{{trim}}

